Not today.

80
00:08:52,953 --> 00:08:54,253
How'd it go?

81
00:08:54,600 --> 00:08:55,899
Not so good.

82
00:08:55,923 --> 00:08:59,037
Director said he's going
to see what he can do.

83
00:09:00,512 --> 00:09:01,591
You all right?

84
00:09:01,615 --> 00:09:05,325
Gotta tamper down,
get it under control.

85
00:09:05,349 --> 00:09:07,831
Hey, put that dictionary on my hand.

86
00:09:08,171 --> 00:09:10,835
It's that book over there,
the orange one. It's a dictionary.

87
00:09:10,859 --> 00:09:13,562
Thanks. I know what a dictionary is.

88
00:09:15,132 --> 00:09:16,432
You know,

89
00:09:16,786 --> 00:09:19,686
there are two kinds
of people in this world:

90
00:09:19,827 --> 00:09:22,226
men of action and everyone else.

91
00:09:53,850 --> 00:09:55,150
Fuck!

92
00:09:57,187 --> 00:09:59,227
All the indications
pointed that direction,

93
00:09:59,251 --> 00:10:01,260
but it wasn't until
the PET scan was complete

94
00:10:01,284 --> 00:10:02,620
that we could be sure.

95
00:10:02,644 --> 00:10:04,135
So, no more memory tests?

96
00:10:04,159 --> 00:10:05,190
Just the opposite.

97
00:10:05,214 --> 00:10:07,126
Mental exercises
are shown to be effective…

98
00:10:07,150 --> 00:10:10,261
All right, what is it?
Eight years and I'm dead?

99
00:10:11,193 --> 00:10:12,493
Mr. Ruchowski,

100
00:10:12,721 --> 00:10:14,021
let me repeat,

101
00:10:14,123 --> 00:10:15,803
this is not Alzheimer's.

102
00:10:16,488 --> 00:10:18,484
For many years,
frontotemporal dementia

103
00:10:18,508 --> 00:10:20,577
and Alzheimer's were confused, but

104
00:10:20,935 --> 00:10:23,389
frontotemporal dementia
is a separate disease.

105
00:10:24,796 --> 00:10:26,096
It's better?

106
00:10:27,685 --> 00:10:30,627
FTD is much more aggressive.

107
00:10:31,252 --> 00:10:32,552
Much more?

108
00:10:32,665 --> 00:10:33,965
How much more?

109
00:10:34,816 --> 00:10:37,437
- Did anyone come with you today?
- No.

110
00:10:37,502 --> 00:10:40,601
Family is very important
in a situation like this.

111
00:10:40,767 --> 00:10:43,853
I don't have any brothers and sisters.
No children.

112
00:10:43,956 --> 00:10:45,280
My work is my family.

113
00:10:45,304 --> 00:10:48,840
I've spoken with Dr. Gross, Nathan Gross,
in the Special Care wing.

114
00:10:48,864 --> 00:10:50,606
Now after we're finished,
you'll pay him a visit.

115
00:10:50,630 --> 00:10:52,059
He's expecting you.

116
00:10:52,083 --> 00:10:54,834
Is this frontal… FTD,

117
00:10:54,868 --> 00:10:58,046
is there anything
I should be on the lookout for?

118
00:10:58,602 --> 00:11:01,226
You will be subject to overreactions

119
00:11:01,250 --> 00:11:03,089
or inappropriate reactions,

120
00:11:03,113 --> 00:11:05,623
blank spells. Perhaps
you've noticed this already.

121
00:11:05,647 --> 00:11:09,099
Mood swings,
unreliable sensory perception.

122
00:11:09,310 --> 00:11:11,516
"Unreliable sensory perception."

123
00:11:11,804 --> 00:11:13,484
That's what it's called.

124
00:11:14,919 --> 00:11:16,137
What is prescribed?

125
00:11:16,161 --> 00:11:18,046
Usually serotonin inhibitors…

126
00:11:18,070 --> 00:11:20,986
Zoloft, Paxil…
or antidepressants.

127
00:11:21,388 --> 00:11:23,371
But those are drugs for crazy people,

128
00:11:23,395 --> 00:11:25,679
manic-depressives. That's not me.

129
00:11:25,752 --> 00:11:28,194
Okay, let's get that clear.
That's not who I am.

130
00:12:16,566 --> 00:12:17,866
John Randall?

131
00:12:18,145 --> 00:12:19,445
Oh, yes.

132
00:12:19,773 --> 00:12:21,621
You are…?
- Charles Ruchowski.

133
00:12:21,645 --> 00:12:23,629
I'm a friend. An acquaintance.

134
00:12:23,660 --> 00:12:25,250
Oh! From the Marine Corps?

135
00:12:25,838 --> 00:12:27,138
Follow me.

136
00:12:32,344 --> 00:12:33,644
John?

137
00:12:34,752 --> 00:12:36,477
John, you have a visitor.

138
00:12:38,879 --> 00:12:40,179
Just pull up a chair.

139
00:12:48,697 --> 00:12:50,454
John, it's Charles.

140
00:12:55,836 --> 00:12:57,629
It's a pleasant day today.

141
00:13:03,491 --> 00:13:05,146
Are you comfortable?

142
00:13:13,110 --> 00:13:16,045
There. Them better?

143
00:13:18,893 --> 00:13:20,577
Would you like me to sing you something?

144
00:13:22,589 --> 00:13:24,245
Would you like that?

145
00:13:26,597 --> 00:13:28,978
From the Halls of Montezuma

146
00:13:30,250 --> 00:13:32,667
To the shores of Tripoli

147
00:13:34,540 --> 00:13:37,036
We fight our country's battles

148
00:13:37,060 --> 00:13:39,924
In the air, on land and sea.

149
00:13:41,151 --> 00:13:45,488
First to fight for right and freedom

150
00:13:47,566 --> 00:13:51,095
And to keep our honor clean

151
00:13:53,554 --> 00:13:57,260
We are proud to claim the title

152
00:13:58,794 --> 00:14:02,107
Of United States Marines.

153
00:14:41,014 --> 00:14:41,783
Yes?

154
00:14:41,847 --> 00:14:42,980
<i>Milton?</i>

155
00:14:43,004 --> 00:14:44,180
Yes.

156
00:14:44,204 --> 00:14:45,998
<i>This is Bob Deacon at NSA.</i>

157
00:14:46,397 --> 00:14:49,768
<i>A while back you put in a watch
for certain chemical compounds.</i>

158
00:14:50,530 --> 00:14:52,147
This is three years ago.

159
00:14:52,171 --> 00:14:54,171
<i>You still interested in that?</i>

160
00:14:54,337 --> 00:14:56,124
- I am.
- Good, something's come up.

161
00:14:56,148 --> 00:14:58,236
Where can I find you?
I'm coming over.

162
00:14:58,383 --> 00:15:00,429
A couple of weeks ago
that flash drive

163
00:15:00,453 --> 00:15:02,936
came into the possession
of the Romanians.

164
00:15:03,596 --> 00:15:06,859
It was water-damaged…
the guy jumped off a bridge.

165
00:15:06,979 --> 00:15:11,258
On it we found Islamic sermons
and medical reports.

166
00:15:11,282 --> 00:15:12,502
That's where you come in.

167
00:15:12,526 --> 00:15:15,439
We ran "Decitabine"
and your request came up.

168
00:15:16,381 --> 00:15:18,528
Who was Abdi Abdikarim?

169
00:15:18,558 --> 00:15:19,870
Kenyan national.

170
00:15:19,894 --> 00:15:22,943
We had some old passport records.
Other than that, nothing.

171
00:15:22,967 --> 00:15:27,044
SRI made inquiries, but the
Kenyans weren't all that much help.

172
00:15:27,068 --> 00:15:29,157
Can I have a copy
of the full document?

173
00:15:29,181 --> 00:15:30,472
There's over 50 pages.

174
00:15:30,503 --> 00:15:32,921
That's all right.
I'll take it electronically.

175
00:15:51,064 --> 00:15:53,113
Muhammad Banir is alive.

176
00:15:53,769 --> 00:15:56,113
They say he's dead…
everybody says he's dead.

177
00:15:56,141 --> 00:15:58,354
Killed in an explosion.
But he's not!

178
00:15:58,378 --> 00:15:59,256
There was a body.

179
00:15:59,280 --> 00:16:02,172
So what?
I didn't see any head.

180
00:16:02,359 --> 00:16:04,580
I didn't see Banir's head.

181
00:16:04,969 --> 00:16:06,269
Mr. Lake.

182
00:16:07,256 --> 00:16:10,941
Mr. Lake, if you wish
to return to work at the CIA,

183
00:16:11,385 --> 00:16:14,857
I strongly recommend you put the
matter of Muhammad Banir behind you.

184
00:16:16,876 --> 00:16:18,176
This job…

185
00:16:18,955 --> 00:16:20,255
is everything.

186
00:16:21,649 --> 00:16:22,949
It's my…

187
00:16:24,056 --> 00:16:25,356
my belief.

188
00:16:51,181 --> 00:16:52,390
Yeah?

189
00:16:52,414 --> 00:16:55,609
<i>Evan, where are you? I've been
trying to reach you. I left messages.</i>

190
00:16:56,700 --> 00:16:58,000
I've been busy.

191
00:16:58,286 --> 00:16:59,667
<i>Something's come up.</i>

192
00:16:59,699 --> 00:17:00,339
What?

193
00:17:00,363 --> 00:17:02,603
<i>I don't wanna talk about it
over an open line.</i>

194
00:17:02,628 --> 00:17:04,904
<i>Where are you?
I'll come meet you.</i>

195
00:17:06,407 --> 00:17:08,062
<i>Evan, where are you?</i>

196
00:17:09,296 --> 00:17:10,952
<i>Evan, where are you?</i>

197
00:17:11,133 --> 00:17:13,306
Diamond Tuesdays.

198
00:17:13,623 --> 00:17:15,303
<i>You're at Ruby Tuesdays?</i>

199
00:17:15,338 --> 00:17:18,648
Yes, I'm at Ruby Tuesdays.
That's what I just said.

200
00:17:18,854 --> 00:17:20,808
<i>Okay, which one?</i>

201
00:17:21,110 --> 00:17:22,410
The one in…

202
00:17:24,971 --> 00:17:26,271
Arlington.

203
00:17:41,738 --> 00:17:43,375
- Ev.
- Yeah?

204
00:17:45,798 --> 00:17:47,161
- Excuse me.
- Yeah?

205
00:17:47,185 --> 00:17:49,468
Get this man
something to eat, please,

206
00:17:49,508 --> 00:17:50,938
and a cup of coffee.

207
00:17:50,962 --> 00:17:52,262
You got it.

208
00:17:57,648 --> 00:17:59,372
Can I clear that for you?

209
00:17:59,810 --> 00:18:01,110
Hey.

210
00:18:02,195 --> 00:18:04,195
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

211
00:18:09,592 --> 00:18:11,385
That wasn't very sociable.

212
00:18:12,566 --> 00:18:13,866
What's going on?

213
00:18:14,598 --> 00:18:15,898
Nothing.

214
00:18:15,979 --> 00:18:17,279
Do you want to talk about it?

215
00:18:17,679 --> 00:18:19,988
What is so goddamn important?

216
00:18:20,453 --> 00:18:22,401
This "something" that has come up.

217
00:18:24,615 --> 00:18:27,421
There's been a possible hit on Banir.

218
00:18:28,612 --> 00:18:31,545
Over the last year,
five requests for Deferiprone

219
00:18:31,569 --> 00:18:32,838
which is not too unusual…

220
00:18:32,862 --> 00:18:34,664
No, it doesn't affect the anemia.

221
00:18:34,688 --> 00:18:36,054
It's just the iron deficiency.

222
00:18:36,078 --> 00:18:39,927
Right, but the same source…
the man requesting it was Kenyan,

223
00:18:40,003 --> 00:18:43,560
but the doctor is
in Bucharest University Hospital,

224
00:18:43,584 --> 00:18:45,462
a research hospital.

225
00:18:45,486 --> 00:18:48,294
Decitabine and Azacitidine,

226
00:18:48,318 --> 00:18:50,532
which are only used
for clinical trials…

227
00:18:50,564 --> 00:18:51,745
Mediterranean anemia.

228
00:18:51,769 --> 00:18:54,096
Thalassemia, which is hereditary,

229
00:18:54,120 --> 00:18:56,315
which we know
Muhammad Banir carries,

230
00:18:56,339 --> 00:18:58,926
even though
he has been dead for 20 years.

231
00:18:58,959 --> 00:19:00,738
You know his father died of it.

232
00:19:00,762 --> 00:19:03,045
And Abdikarim,
the man procuring the drug,

233
00:19:03,069 --> 00:19:06,338
was a suspect in a Nigerian fraud ring.

234
00:19:06,362 --> 00:19:10,105
Rather than give himself up,
he jumps off a bridge.

235
00:19:10,458 --> 00:19:13,641
Medical info was on a flash drive.

236
00:19:14,278 --> 00:19:16,030
He ain't no Kenyan.

237
00:19:16,536 --> 00:19:19,157
Abdikarim is a fucking raghead name.

238
00:19:19,517 --> 00:19:21,923
What? I got nothing against ragheads.

239
00:19:21,947 --> 00:19:23,169
Except maybe there are too many of them.

240
00:19:23,193 --> 00:19:24,848
He was 100% healthy.

241
00:19:24,941 --> 00:19:25,875
What else?

242
00:19:25,899 --> 00:19:27,199
Nothing.

243
00:19:27,415 --> 00:19:29,095
I knew he didn't die.

244
00:19:29,229 --> 00:19:32,540
This means his condition
has moved to an advanced stage.

245
00:19:32,572 --> 00:19:34,942
Now he can lay low,
he can become invisible,

246
00:19:34,969 --> 00:19:38,279
but sooner or later
the disease will flush him out.

247
00:19:39,010 --> 00:19:40,310
Banir's got it.

248
00:19:41,844 --> 00:19:43,144
It's come out.

249
00:19:44,427 --> 00:19:45,916
It's in his blood.

250
00:19:48,889 --> 00:19:51,648
<i>These are the blood cells of the
antagonist of our story.</i>

251
00:19:51,705 --> 00:19:55,468
<i>The red cells suffer from a lack of
hemoglobin and excess of iron.</i>

252
00:19:55,533 --> 00:19:58,177
<i>The symptoms are fatigue, jaundice,</i>

253
00:19:58,201 --> 00:20:00,640
<i>leading to an enlarged spleen
and bone deformity.</i>

254
00:20:00,671 --> 00:20:03,450
<i>Unset, occurs relatively early in life.</i>

255
00:20:03,474 --> 00:20:05,154
<i>There is no known cure.</i>

256
00:21:39,241 --> 00:21:41,437
I've come across intelligence
which leads me to believe…

257
00:21:41,461 --> 00:21:43,141
Muhammad Banir is alive.

258
00:21:43,417 --> 00:21:44,138
Go on.

259
00:21:44,162 --> 00:21:46,649
Banir was believed killed
during my extraction.

260
00:21:46,737 --> 00:21:50,095
Not a word about him has been heard
for 22 years… until now.

261
00:21:50,143 --> 00:21:53,420
Banir has a hereditary
